r","organization":"D.H. Lamb & Co.","location":"Cleveland, Cuyahoga County, Ohio","start_year":1835,"end_year":1841,"notes":"Per obituary: 'lawyery at D.H. Lamb & Co.' EH 1909 says 'engaged in soda manufacture' — D.H. Lamb & Co. may have been the soda manufacturing enterprise for which Edward served as legal counsel and commercial partner. Removed from Rochester NY to Cleveland 1835; remained until his death August 1, 1841 at thirty-nine."}],"military_service":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST043","relationship":"alumnus","years":"graduated 1820","institution_blurb":"Graduated Williams College 1820."}],"landmarks":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"artworks":[],"tags":["lawyer","ohio_migration"],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"death","header":"Died at thirty-nine; wife outlived him fifty years","body":"Edward left West Hampton MA as a Williams College graduate, practiced law in Ohio and Massachusetts, then pivoted to soda manufacturing in Cleveland — dying there August 1, 1841 at only thirty-nine, leaving two children under age seven. His wife Mary Ann Dwight survived him until June 4, 1891, outliving him by exactly fifty years."},{"number":2,"category":"character","header":"Became, late in life, a man of prayer","body":"The obituary that marked Edward's death at thirty-nine focused less on his law practice at D.H. Lamb & Co. than on the man he had become: late in life he united with the Congregational Church in Ohio City and was remembered by those who knew him simply as 'a man of prayer.' For a direct descendant of Rev. Thomas Hooker — who helped establish the Congregational tradition in Connecticut two centuries earlier — the phrase carried the full weight of inheritance."},{"number":3,"category":"career","header":"Williams 1820; youngest son of a man who","body":"Edward Hooker graduated Williams College in 1820 and practiced law at Ravenna Ohio, then South Hadley Massachusetts, before settling in Cleveland 